emplateSpringTestCase`. That might be a good approach to explore!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating JUnit discovery**\\n\\nI'm trying to assess if the scanner can find it. I might inspect the JUnit discovery code or cache, but it seems there's no run happening. The JUnit Platform discovery selectors select classpath roots and send requests to all engines. I’m wondering if the Jupiter engine’s classpath scanning includes nested classes. I recall that `ReflectionSupport.findAllClassesInClasspathRoot(root, predicate, classNameFilter)` finds all classes excluding certain patterns. Should I consider using `javap` or perhaps grep in the sources? It might be useful to check the cache source jar too.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_hu3Oh3soshr4ntZe4jgncUlK|fc_0f0e3408191c9cfe016a282264da7c8196bdcfbf7163e950bc", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "find ~/.gradle/caches/modules-2/files-2.1/org.junit.jupiter/junit-jupiter-engine/6.0.3 -name '*sources.jar' -print -o -name '*.jar' -print | head -10 && find ~/.gradle/caches/modules-2/files-2.1/org.junit.platform/junit-platform-commons/6.0.3 -type f | head", "timeout": 10}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "oca/gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 4303, "output": 946, "cacheRead": 38400, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 43649, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1781015115478, "responseId": "resp_0f0e3408191c9cfe016a28224c0e6c8196a716ba42ce70a360"}}
