[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Exploring JUnit discovery**\n\nI’m figuring out how JUnit Jupiter discovers classes through classpath scanning. It seems like it scans all `.class` files but may exclude nested ones unless specifically selected. They introduced support for `@ClassTemplate` nested classes, so I’m considering if a static nested fixture gets detected as a nested class. Alternatively, I could create a public top-level class in a separate file, but I need to be cautious about the one-to-one rule for class coverage in dedicated test files. A helper fixture might work under `src/test/java`.\n\n**Considering test class structure**\n\nI'm thinking about the importance of maintaining a one-to-one mapping between dynamic-access report classes and their corresponding test class files. It seems like the rule is to avoid creating extra test class files. I wonder if making `ClassTemplateSpringTestCase` a public static nested class within `TestClassScannerTest` would allow the scanner to recognize `TestClassScannerTest` as a test class, including the nested `ClassTemplateSpringTestCase`. That might be a good approach to explore!\n\n**Evaluating JUnit discovery**\n\nI'm trying to assess if the scanner can find it. I might inspect the JUnit discovery code or cache, but it seems there's no run happening. The JUnit Platform discovery selectors select classpath roots and send requests to all engines. I’m wondering if the Jupiter engine’s classpath scanning includes nested classes. I recall that `ReflectionSupport.findAllClassesInClasspathRoot(root, predicate, classNameFilter)` finds all classes excluding certain patterns. Should I consider using `javap` or perhaps grep in the sources? It might be useful to check the cache source jar too.", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_0f0e3408191c9cfe016a28224df784819690d05671d518e84c\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"content\":[],\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABqK